cales as {\$}\backslashtau{\_}{\{}spin{\}} = \backslashtau{\_}{\{}mass{\}} 1.5k/\backslashsqrt{\{}\backslasheta{\_}{\{}\backslashast{\}}{\}}{\$}, where {\$}\backslashtau{\_}{\{}mass{\}} \backslashequiv M/{\{}\backslashdot M{\}}{\$} is the characteristic mass loss time, and {\$}k{\$} is the dimensionless factor for stellar moment of inertia. The full numerical scaling relation we cite gives typical spindown times of order 1 Myr for several known magnetic massive stars.},
